snippet.textDisplay:
The Taiwan Lantern Festival is being held in Taichung from February 8 through February 23, 2020. Falun Dafa practitioners in Taiwan have participated in this important festival during the Chinese Lunar New Year for many years.

Their entry, a three-story-high Falun Dafa boat lantern drew many event attendees. The boat took a year to make and has 12 large lotus petals on the boat body, nine Falun emblems on the sails, and three flags with words “Truthfulness, Compassion, and Forbearance” on the mast. It shines brightly at night.

Many visitors boarded the Falun Dafa Boat lantern and took photos and videos. Practitioners have also been on site to teach the exercises and help the public learn more about Falun Dafa, also called Falun Gong.

snippet.textDisplay:
First time I have seen this show, so I do not have a previous episode to compare it to. This was a very deep interview (Panorama type), where some very tough questions were asked, and answered.

The interviewer, might come across more amicable to the guest & audience (I notice many commentators below, questioned whether the host was more hostile in this interview, than she typically with male guests), if less intrusive questions are asked first (e.g. new releases, signing etc.), and then, as the guest relaxes more, and the rapport between interviewer and interviewee grows, more difficult questions (e.g. past relationships, colourism) are asked.

The many deep scrutinous questions, may be a reason why other celebrities / artists etc. may choose not to go on the show (the host mentioned female artists etc. not wanting to come on the show).

Wondered if telling interviewees to come prepared with a couple of no holds barred questions for the host, would demonstrate the host is not out to get anyone, but just wanting to know the answers to various questions she has thought about in the past about her guest.

Both host and guest came across as highly intelligent, articulative, assertive, professional people. Great interview.
